WEBVTT

00:01.876 --> 00:04.170
♪ ♪

00:28.027 --> 00:31.448
♪ ♪

00:59.225 --> 01:42.393
♪ ♪

01:42.393 --> 01:44.854
Good morning, West Beverly.

01:44.938 --> 01:46.314
And good morning, David Silver,

01:46.397 --> 01:48.399
(over P.A.):
wherever you are.

01:55.949 --> 01:58.868
Oh, and David, if you think
I'm going to cut you any

01:58.952 --> 02:02.163
kind of slack because you think
you've become

02:02.247 --> 02:04.332
some kind
of major recording star,

02:04.415 --> 02:06.042
well, you can forget about it.

02:06.125 --> 02:09.086
And if anyone out there
has seen David,

02:09.169 --> 02:09.461
you can tell him he's late...

02:09.545 --> 02:11.339
as usual.

02:20.306 --> 02:22.350
♪ ♪

02:34.028 --> 02:35.238
{\an1}Well, look what
the cat dragged in.

02:35.321 --> 02:37.240
Good morning.

02:37.323 --> 02:38.741
Nice of you to show up.

02:38.825 --> 02:40.201
I'm sorry, I was...

02:40.285 --> 02:41.578
{\an1}Up all night
at the studio again?

02:41.661 --> 02:43.413
Or were you out at some club
partying with the producers?

02:43.496 --> 02:46.916
{\an3}No, actually I was
studying for a trig midterm.

02:47.000 --> 02:49.752
{\an1}Oh, and I didn't think
rock stars had to study.

02:49.836 --> 02:51.588
{\an3}Well, I'm not a
rock star, Donna.

02:51.671 --> 02:53.089
Of course you are, David.

02:53.173 --> 02:55.884
{\an1}Ladies and gentlemen,
let me take this opportunity

02:55.967 --> 02:57.260
{\an1}to announce that
our very own David Silver

02:57.343 --> 03:00.346
has just signed
with Donna...ords.

03:00.430 --> 03:02.307
{\an1}David, please
do not be modest.

03:02.390 --> 03:05.935
{\an1}And if all his songs
are as great as this one,

03:06.019 --> 03:07.937
we know they'll all be hits.

03:08.021 --> 03:11.107
(hip-hop beat begins)

03:11.190 --> 03:12.901
What'd you have to
go and do that for?

03:12.984 --> 03:14.277
'Cause I'm proud of you.

03:14.360 --> 03:15.236
Well, don't you think

03:15.320 --> 03:17.280
{\an3}you spread the hype on
a little too thick?

03:17.363 --> 03:19.991
{\an3}I mean, they're paying
me absolute minimum

03:20.074 --> 03:21.451
{\an3}and we're only doing
a couple of demos.

03:21.534 --> 03:23.828
{\an3}And it all depends on whether
they like what they hear.

03:23.912 --> 03:25.288
{\an1}David, they're
going to like it.

03:25.371 --> 03:27.290
{\an1}Come on, listen to this.
It's great.

03:27.373 --> 03:29.751
♪ And I'm not going to sit
back, back and relax ♪

03:29.834 --> 03:31.127
♪ While brothers kill
each other... ♪

03:31.210 --> 03:32.462
Yeah, I guess it is.

03:32.545 --> 03:36.090
Um, listen,

03:36.174 --> 03:38.468
{\an1}I've never really been
to a recording studio before.

03:38.551 --> 03:39.636
You think I can come?

03:39.719 --> 03:40.303
♪ Um-um, clearing my throat... ♪

03:40.386 --> 03:42.430
I don't know.

03:42.513 --> 03:44.098
{\an1}Well, I promise
I won't get in the way.

03:44.182 --> 03:47.101
{\an1}I'll be like
Yoko Ono or something.

03:47.185 --> 03:48.478
{\an3}Well, that doesn't exactly
fill me with confidence.

03:48.561 --> 03:50.480
{\an1}Well, I mean, you won't
even know I'm there. Please?

03:50.563 --> 03:53.274
Listen, Donna,
if you do come,

03:53.358 --> 03:54.442
you have to do me a
favor and promise me

03:54.525 --> 03:56.819
{\an3}you'll just blend in
with the woodwork.

03:56.903 --> 03:58.154
Okay, I promise.

03:58.237 --> 04:00.114
I won't say a word.

04:09.582 --> 04:12.293
HeyYeah?sh.

04:12.377 --> 04:14.462
I hear the NBA's been
treating you pretty good lately.

04:14.545 --> 04:16.047
Yeah, who told you that?

04:16.130 --> 04:17.757
A little birdie.

04:17.839 --> 04:19.341
{\an1}You know I book
a little action myself.

04:19.425 --> 04:21.052
{\an1}Mostly for the guys
on the football team,

04:21.135 --> 04:21.594
{\an1}but if you ever need
a connection,

04:21.678 --> 04:24.180
I'll be happy to help.

04:24.263 --> 04:25.306
Okay.

04:25.390 --> 04:27.225
Later.

04:30.103 --> 04:32.021
Steve, do me a favor.

04:32.105 --> 04:34.065
{\an3}Don't be giving my name
out to bookies, all right?

04:34.148 --> 04:35.525
{\an3}It's not exactly
the reputation I want.

04:35.608 --> 04:37.694
It wasn't me.

04:37.777 --> 04:38.528
Then who was it?

04:38.611 --> 04:40.697
Word gets around, Brandon.

04:40.780 --> 04:42.031
You're a major player.

04:42.115 --> 04:42.949
{\an3}I'm not a major
player, okay?

04:43.032 --> 04:44.200
{\an3}My gambling days
are numbered.

04:44.283 --> 04:45.576
{\an3}The basketball
season's almost over.

04:45.660 --> 04:46.494
Yeah, but then there's baseball

04:46.577 --> 04:48.579
and then field hockey

04:48.663 --> 04:51.040
{\an3}and that turtle racing
you love so much.

04:51.124 --> 04:52.375
Very funny.

04:55.461 --> 04:56.963
Are you okay?

04:57.046 --> 04:58.214
I don't know.

04:58.298 --> 04:59.424
{\an1}I mean, I think so,
sometimes,

04:59.507 --> 05:01.759
{\an1}and then everything
just brings me down again.

05:01.843 --> 05:03.761
Being here doesn't help.

05:03.845 --> 05:06.723
{\an3}Well, maybe
just for today,

05:06.806 --> 05:08.266
{\an3}just while we're here,
you can pretend

05:08.349 --> 05:11.060
{\an3}we're in, like,
Hawaii or something.

05:11.144 --> 05:13.521
I don't think so.

05:13.604 --> 05:15.732
{\an3}I guess that was a pretty
stupid thing to say.

05:15.815 --> 05:17.191
Sorry.

05:17.275 --> 05:19.444
Hi.

05:19.527 --> 05:21.404
Hi.

05:21.487 --> 05:23.072
How're you doing today?

05:23.156 --> 05:24.949
I'm all right, I guess.

05:25.033 --> 05:28.077
Listen, I was wondering--
I don't know what you guys

05:28.161 --> 05:29.245
are doing tonight,
but I though that

05:29.328 --> 05:30.538
maybe you'd like to come over
to my house for dinner.

05:30.621 --> 05:33.833
My mom's kind of worried
about you.

05:34.667 --> 05:35.585
Unless, of course,
you're busy.

05:35.668 --> 05:39.255
No, we're not busy.

05:39.338 --> 05:41.257
Great, then I'll see you
tonight.

05:41.340 --> 05:42.425
Okay.

05:42.508 --> 05:45.178
Tell your mom thSure.

05:49.015 --> 05:50.224
You don't mind, do you?

05:50.308 --> 05:52.101
No, of course not.

05:56.022 --> 05:58.566
{\an3}How 'bout this issue--
October 17.

05:58.649 --> 06:00.985
{\an3}We had the Bonnie
Bernstein piece

06:01.069 --> 06:02.028
{\an3}on foreign
exchange students,

06:02.111 --> 06:05.239
{\an3}and your article on
high school contributions

06:05.323 --> 06:06.282
{\an3}to the Somalian relief
fund was excellent.

06:06.365 --> 06:08.534
{\an1}Two stories you can be sure
every other high school

06:08.618 --> 06:10.745
{\an1}in the country
has done... twice.

06:10.828 --> 06:12.914
Then I think we should go
with our first instincts

06:12.997 --> 06:15.249
{\an3}and focus on the issue
with Brandon's editorial

06:15.333 --> 06:16.292
{\an3}on the cancelled
football game.

06:16.375 --> 06:18.294
Oh, but the rest
of that issue stinks.

06:18.377 --> 06:19.504
Come on, Andrea,
it doesn't stink.

06:19.587 --> 06:21.756
Gil, let's face it.

06:21.839 --> 06:22.715
Almost everything
we've done this year stinks.

06:22.799 --> 06:25.301
You nailed it the day
you walked in here.

06:25.384 --> 06:27.261
<i>The Blaze</i> is okay,
it's passable.

06:27.345 --> 06:29.097
{\an1}But we have not
published one issue

06:29.180 --> 06:30.973
{\an1}distinctive enough
to win us any awards.

06:31.057 --> 06:34.185
That may be so, but you're being
much too hypercritical.

06:34.268 --> 06:34.685
Isn't she?

06:34.769 --> 06:36.979
Isn't she always?

06:37.063 --> 06:38.648
{\an1}You guys,
I have reason to be.

06:38.731 --> 06:40.608
{\an1}Look at this, we received
another entry form

06:40.691 --> 06:41.984
for a high school
journalism award.

06:42.068 --> 06:45.196
This one sends the winning
editors on a trip to D.C.

06:45.279 --> 06:46.531
{\an3}Really?

06:46.614 --> 06:47.657
Well, don't pack your bags,
Brandon.

06:47.740 --> 06:50.660
It's not like we're going to win
any awards this year.

06:50.743 --> 06:52.203
You know, that's one thing

06:52.286 --> 06:53.955
{\an3}I really like
about you, Andrea.

06:54.038 --> 06:55.540
{\an3}It's your
positive attitude.

06:55.623 --> 06:58.668
Look, I'm just
being realistic, okay?

06:58.751 --> 07:00.878
I mean, Gil and I have spent
the last hour

07:00.962 --> 07:02.296
going over back issues.

07:02.380 --> 07:03.923
There is nothing here.

07:04.006 --> 07:06.717
{\an3}Andrea, the year's
not over yet.

07:06.801 --> 07:08.136
Well, we better hurry up.

07:08.219 --> 07:10.221
We publish three more issues
before the contest deadline,

07:10.304 --> 07:11.556
and I want the Class of '93
to be remembered.

07:12.598 --> 07:15.518
I want to be remembered.

07:15.601 --> 07:18.020
Don't worry, Andrea.

07:18.104 --> 07:19.981
We'll remember you.

07:21.607 --> 07:24.527
(lush pop intro playing)

07:24.610 --> 07:26.320
I did a little noodling
over the weekend

07:26.404 --> 07:27.989
and I think I have it here.

07:28.072 --> 07:29.907
This is the feel
we need on this song.

07:29.991 --> 07:32.034
Now, I know it's
not what you're used to.

07:32.118 --> 07:32.702
I just want you to listen to it,

07:32.785 --> 07:35.163
just groove on it.

07:35.246 --> 07:37.165
You feel it?

07:38.124 --> 07:40.209
You feel it?

07:40.293 --> 07:41.919
Uh, it's... it's different.

07:42.003 --> 07:44.046
{\an1}Of course it's different.
It has to be different.

07:44.130 --> 07:46.048
{\an1}Who wants more of the same?
Now here, listen to this.

07:46.132 --> 07:47.258
Hey, listen.

07:47.341 --> 07:49.218
(lush, synthesized orchestra
playing with David's vocals)

07:49.302 --> 07:50.428
Oh, is that great?

07:50.511 --> 07:52.054
(music clicks off)hat?

07:52.138 --> 07:55.141
Yeah, I-I guess it is.

07:57.268 --> 07:58.936
What do you think?

07:59.020 --> 08:01.230
Uh, well, don't ask me.

08:01.314 --> 08:02.190
{\an1}I don't really know
that much about music.

08:02.273 --> 08:05.234
Well, you know what
you like, don't you?

08:05.318 --> 08:05.735
Come on, tell him.

08:05.818 --> 08:08.070
It's fabulous.

08:10.364 --> 08:11.908
David, it's fabulous.

08:11.991 --> 08:13.075
You see?

08:13.159 --> 08:14.535
She knows.

08:14.619 --> 08:15.786
I know, Davey...

08:15.870 --> 08:17.914
It's perfect.

08:22.835 --> 08:25.463
{\an1}David, why are you
recording this song?

08:25.546 --> 08:28.090
{\an3}You heard what Serge
said, he likes it.

08:28.174 --> 08:30.092
{\an1}Yeah, but I thought you
were going to go with hip-hop.

08:30.176 --> 08:31.093
Rap, you know, the hot stuff.

08:31.177 --> 08:33.261
Which is exactly what
I tried telling him,

08:33.346 --> 08:34.764
{\an3}but he said that this
song is commercial.

08:34.847 --> 08:38.142
{\an1}Well, I guess he
knows what's best.

08:40.895 --> 08:42.980
(classic rock 'n' roll
ballad playing)

08:43.063 --> 08:45.107
(entrance bell chimes)

08:48.736 --> 08:50.571
{\an1}Hi, Duke.
How are you doing?

08:50.655 --> 08:51.447
You remember me?

08:51.530 --> 08:52.823
We met last year
at the racetrack.

08:52.907 --> 08:53.950
Oh, yeah, sure.

08:54.033 --> 08:54.951
{\an3}How you doing,
sweetheart?

08:55.034 --> 08:56.953
Good.

08:57.036 --> 08:59.121
Hey, big Hey.

08:59.205 --> 08:59.997
Can I get you anything?

09:00.081 --> 09:03.125
{\an3}Nah, just here
on a little busineAh.

09:08.214 --> 09:10.049
Hey, busy, kid?

09:10.132 --> 09:11.300
Yeah, sort of.

09:11.384 --> 09:12.677
{\an1}Me, too. That's why this'll
only take a minute.

09:12.760 --> 09:16.013
Can we step outside?

09:16.097 --> 09:19.058
{\an3}Sure. Just let me tell
Nat I'm gonna be a minute.

09:22.061 --> 09:23.604
Sure thing, kid.

09:28.818 --> 09:32.238
We had a conversation
a couple of weeks ago.

09:32.321 --> 09:34.198
{\an3}In case you've
forgotten,

09:34.282 --> 09:36.659
{\an3}maybe I should
refresh your memory.

09:36.742 --> 09:37.994
No, I remember
what you said.

09:38.077 --> 09:39.078
Then where's my money?

09:39.161 --> 09:41.872
{\an3}I said I'd let you slide one
time and one time only.

09:41.956 --> 09:44.000
And I paid you every cent.

09:44.083 --> 09:45.126
That was the last time.

09:45.209 --> 09:47.211
{\an3}Where's the money
you owe me now?

09:49.714 --> 09:50.298
I'll, I'll get it.

09:50.381 --> 09:51.841
I just need a few days, Duke.

09:51.924 --> 09:54.010
I like you.

09:54.093 --> 09:56.679
I do.

09:56.762 --> 09:58.973
But this guy in my car--

09:59.056 --> 10:00.182
that's Tony--

10:00.266 --> 10:03.185
{\an3}and Tony, he doesn't
like anybody.

10:03.269 --> 10:05.855
{\an3}So, you know how much
you owe us, right?

10:05.938 --> 10:07.898
Yeah.

10:07.982 --> 10:10.026
It's a lot of money, kid.

10:10.109 --> 10:11.527
You got till Friday.

10:14.280 --> 10:17.241
(car door opens, engine starts)

10:19.910 --> 10:22.913
Well, who wants some seconds?

10:22.997 --> 10:24.081
Without Jim and Brandon here,

10:24.165 --> 10:25.791
{\an3}there's practically
a whole pie left.

10:25.875 --> 10:27.376
{\an1}None for me, Mom,
I'm stuffed.

10:27.460 --> 10:28.878
Dylan?

10:28.961 --> 10:30.379
Yeah, thanks.

10:30.463 --> 10:33.007
You know, it seems like

10:33.090 --> 10:33.883
{\an1}the first meal
I've had in a few days.

10:33.966 --> 10:36.010
{\an1}It's certainly the first
one I've tasted.

10:36.093 --> 10:37.928
Well, you come here as much
as you want, Dylan.

10:38.012 --> 10:39.347
BRENDA:
Yeah, no matter what.

10:39.430 --> 10:40.556
Remember, this is home.

10:40.639 --> 10:40.848
Thanks, Bren.

10:44.977 --> 10:46.562
Why am I doing this?

10:46.645 --> 10:47.938
{\an3}I'm supposed to
be on a diet.

10:48.022 --> 10:49.065
Would somebody
please stop me?

10:49.148 --> 10:50.358
Save me from myself.

10:50.441 --> 10:52.568
Now, what do you need
to diet for, Kelly?

10:52.651 --> 10:55.363
{\an1}That's what I keep
asking her.

10:55.446 --> 10:56.781
{\an3}Well, we've been eating
so much junk food

10:56.864 --> 10:59.784
{\an3}the past few weeks, I
must've gained five pounds.

10:59.867 --> 11:01.619
So, do like I do:

11:01.702 --> 11:03.913
{\an3}Eat today,
diet tomorrow.

11:03.996 --> 11:05.915
{\an3}Someday, Dylan, that's
going to catch up with you.

11:05.998 --> 11:06.749
{\an1}Yeah, but till then,
pass the pie.

11:06.832 --> 11:08.918
{\an1}BRENDA:
Brandon, better get in here

11:09.001 --> 11:10.252
quick, the pie
is going fast.

11:10.336 --> 11:12.213
{\an3}I didn't think you'd be home
for dinner tonight, honey.

11:12.296 --> 11:14.006
{\an3}I thought you and Dad
were both working late.

11:14.090 --> 11:16.133
Nah, things were kind of slow
and Nat said

11:16.217 --> 11:16.926
he'd close up by himself.

11:17.009 --> 11:18.219
{\an3}Oh, well, I'll
set you a place.

11:18.302 --> 11:19.595
{\an1}No, Mom,
that's all right.

11:19.678 --> 11:20.930
I'm not really hungry
and I've got a lot

11:21.013 --> 11:23.307
Brandon, just sit down
and eat something.

11:23.391 --> 11:23.766
{\an1}Mom, listen to what
I'm saying here.

11:23.849 --> 11:27.103
I'Brandon...!y.

11:30.147 --> 11:31.816
Sorry, I've just
got a lot on my mind.

11:31.899 --> 11:33.859
Apparently.

11:33.943 --> 11:36.404
Brandon, have you
met these people?

11:36.487 --> 11:37.947
Yeah. Hi, guys.

11:38.030 --> 11:39.907
Tough day at the office?

11:39.990 --> 11:41.617
Something like that.

11:41.700 --> 11:43.953
{\an3}Mrs. Walsh, I hate
to eat and run,

11:44.036 --> 11:45.955
but I told my Mom I'd
be home early tonight.

11:46.038 --> 11:47.581
{\an3}DYLAN:
Thanks, it was great.

11:47.665 --> 11:49.792
I'm glad to see you relaxing
a little bit, Dylan.

11:49.875 --> 11:50.292
I'll get coats.

11:50.376 --> 11:53.254
See ya. later, man.

12:06.934 --> 12:08.436
Dylan, don't take me home yet.

12:08.519 --> 12:10.146
Let's go to your house.

12:10.229 --> 12:12.148
I thought you said you
had to be home early.

12:12.231 --> 12:14.608
That's what I told the Walshes.

12:20.948 --> 12:23.492
Not tonight, Kel.

12:26.704 --> 12:29.665
You know, you haven't wanted
to be alone with me in days.

12:29.748 --> 12:30.958
What's the matter with you?

12:31.041 --> 12:32.126
How can you ask me that?

12:32.209 --> 12:33.002
You know what's the matter.

12:33.085 --> 12:35.546
Then let me help you.

12:35.629 --> 12:37.798
Don't keep pushing me away.

12:39.133 --> 12:42.678
{\an3}I haven't been sleeping,
I'm tired...

12:45.931 --> 12:48.559
{\an1}All right.

12:48.642 --> 12:50.561
{\an3}I'm sorry.

12:50.644 --> 12:51.854
That's all right.

12:51.937 --> 12:53.981
Just take me home.

12:58.903 --> 13:00.070
(door opens)

13:00.154 --> 13:01.489
Hi, honey.

13:01.572 --> 13:02.740
{\an1}Hi, baby.

13:02.823 --> 13:04.575
How'dOh...er go?

13:04.658 --> 13:07.203
{\an3}well, Brenda and Kelly
and Dylan were fine.

13:07.286 --> 13:08.078
{\an3}It's Brandon I'm
worried about.

13:08.162 --> 13:10.164
What's the matter?

13:10.247 --> 13:12.917
{\an3}I don't know,
he just seems...

13:13.000 --> 13:15.377
{\an3}distracted.

13:15.461 --> 13:17.505
I'll talk to him.

13:23.969 --> 13:24.929
(knocking)

13:27.473 --> 13:28.849
Can I come in?

13:28.933 --> 13:29.934
Sure.

13:36.649 --> 13:38.067
Ooh, what's this?

13:38.150 --> 13:41.362
Jose Canseco rookie card.

13:41.445 --> 13:43.781
{\an1}Oh! Must be worth
six or seven bucks.

13:43.864 --> 13:45.616
Twenty, if it's mint.

13:45.699 --> 13:46.408
Whew!

13:48.661 --> 13:50.579
{\an1}You've got some
great cards here.

13:50.663 --> 13:51.789
Yeah, they're okay.

13:51.872 --> 13:53.582
Nothing outstanding.

13:53.666 --> 13:55.209
{\an3}I'm actually thinking about
getting them appraised.

13:55.292 --> 13:57.294
Maybe selling them.

13:58.170 --> 14:00.256
What's going on, Brandon?

14:00.339 --> 14:03.217
{\an1}One week you're
buying skis and stereos.

14:03.300 --> 14:04.802
{\an1}The next week,
you're talking about

14:04.885 --> 14:06.011
{\an1}selling off
your baseball cards.

14:06.095 --> 14:07.221
{\an1}What's wrong
with this picture?

14:07.304 --> 14:09.098
There's nothing
going on, Dad.

14:09.181 --> 14:11.559
{\an3}I told you, I'm not
necessarily selling them.

14:11.642 --> 14:12.893
I'm just looking into it.

14:14.853 --> 14:16.647
{\an1}Brandon, I know
you've been gambling.

14:16.730 --> 14:17.314
Dad...

14:17.398 --> 14:19.066
{\an1}You know,
I was never a guy

14:19.149 --> 14:20.609
{\an1}who believed in
get-rich-quick schemes.

14:20.693 --> 14:22.945
{\an1}Probably why
I never got rich.

14:23.028 --> 14:25.072
{\an1}But gambling--
it's just not worth it.

14:25.155 --> 14:26.782
The house always wins.

14:26.865 --> 14:27.950
I know that.

14:28.033 --> 14:28.826
Then why do you do it?

14:28.909 --> 14:30.828
Dad, I just bet on
a couple of games.

14:30.911 --> 14:32.162
It's no big deal.

14:32.246 --> 14:35.124
You're not in any trouble?

14:35.207 --> 14:36.584
Of course not.

14:39.545 --> 14:41.130
Look son, if you
have a problem...

14:41.213 --> 14:44.133
Dad, I don't have
a problem, okay?

14:44.216 --> 14:47.761
{\an3}God, how many times do I
have to repeat myself?

14:47.845 --> 14:48.846
Okay... okay, okay.

15:21.420 --> 15:22.504
Steve, wait!

15:22.588 --> 15:24.173
{\an1}Donna.

15:24.256 --> 15:24.840
What are you doing here
soI, uh,?

15:24.923 --> 15:25.424
I wanted to
talk to you.

15:25.507 --> 15:27.551
{\an3}Listen, I need
a favor.

15:27.635 --> 15:29.011
Anything for you.

15:29.094 --> 15:30.846
{\an3}Actually, it's
for David.

15:30.929 --> 15:31.347
Then forget it.

15:31.430 --> 15:33.015
No, Steve, listen.

15:33.098 --> 15:34.850
{\an3}I was in the studio
with David last night

15:34.933 --> 15:36.644
and something is
definitely wrong.

15:36.727 --> 15:38.312
Look, I don't want
to hear it, okay?

15:38.395 --> 15:39.938
In case you've forgotten,
I'm no longer his manager.

15:40.022 --> 15:40.689
I'm not interested

15:40.773 --> 15:42.316
{\an1}in being his armchair
quarterback,

15:42.399 --> 15:43.901
{\an1}and I certainly don't want
to be his shrink, okay?

15:43.984 --> 15:44.526
It's his gig.

15:44.610 --> 15:45.194
{\an1}And I'm late
for detention.

15:45.277 --> 15:47.237
Steve, wait.

15:47.321 --> 15:49.865
{\an3}This producer Menkon is
ruining everything.

15:49.948 --> 15:51.367
{\an3}He's not picking David's
best material

15:51.450 --> 15:53.160
{\an3}and then he's making
it even worse.

15:53.243 --> 15:54.370
Please.

15:54.453 --> 15:56.205
I know how angry you are.

15:56.288 --> 15:57.831
{\an3}But you're the only one
that can help him.

15:57.915 --> 15:58.999
{\an1}Well, he should have
thought of that

15:59.083 --> 15:59.333
before he blew me off.

15:59.416 --> 16:01.710
{\an3}I know.

16:01.794 --> 16:02.878
{\an3}And David feels
terrible.

16:02.961 --> 16:04.046
He didn't want
to cut you out.

16:04.129 --> 16:05.881
What, they held a gun
Tto his head?.

16:05.964 --> 16:06.590
{\an1}I don't think so,
Donna.

16:06.674 --> 16:08.342
{\an1}People do what they want
to do.

16:08.425 --> 16:10.052
Steve, you're his friend.

16:10.135 --> 16:11.720
Besides, at this point,

16:11.804 --> 16:12.554
he hasn't cut you out
of anything.

16:12.638 --> 16:14.556
Ten percent of nothing
is nothing.

16:14.640 --> 16:15.933
You're there. You have a mouth.

16:16.016 --> 16:17.059
{\an1}Yeah...

16:17.142 --> 16:18.894
and the only reason David
allowed me to come

16:18.977 --> 16:20.604
is because I promised not
to say anything.

16:21.772 --> 16:23.023
Steve, please,

16:23.107 --> 16:24.525
will you just come and see
what's going on?

16:28.987 --> 16:31.407
{\an3}Put, uh, $15 on UCLA
for me, will ya?

16:31.490 --> 16:32.241
Oh, big spender, Miller.

16:32.324 --> 16:34.410
{\an3}Come on, you're
on a roll.

16:34.493 --> 16:35.619
{\an3}Might as well make
some dough.

16:35.703 --> 16:36.829
I'm in for $30.

16:36.912 --> 16:38.080
You got it, Stuart.

16:38.163 --> 16:40.082
Any other takers?

16:40.165 --> 16:41.250
{\an1}Morning,
gentlemen.

16:41.333 --> 16:42.793
Hiya, Walsh.

16:42.876 --> 16:43.877
Would you do me a favor?

16:43.961 --> 16:45.879
Tell Miller that he's betting
like an old lady?

16:45.963 --> 16:46.839
Hey,

16:46.922 --> 16:48.966
{\an1}just make sure you pay up
when I win, will ya?

16:50.968 --> 16:53.095
(laughing)

16:53.178 --> 16:55.973
{\an1}So, how do you keep track
of your bets, Jeff--

16:56.056 --> 16:57.933
{\an1}flash paper
in your locker?

16:58.016 --> 16:59.101
Yeah, right.

16:59.184 --> 17:01.270
{\an3}You been watching too
many old movies, Walsh.

17:01.353 --> 17:03.272
This is the age
of electronics.

17:03.355 --> 17:05.273
{\an3}Everybody's got
a code name.

17:05.357 --> 17:07.276
{\an3}I use the Vegas
point spread.

17:07.358 --> 17:08.819
Very professional.

17:08.902 --> 17:10.820
{\an3}Full-service
operation, Walsh.

17:10.904 --> 17:12.698
{\an3}You bet with me,
I pay on time

17:12.781 --> 17:13.949
{\an3}and I even save
you the cost

17:14.031 --> 17:15.951
of a phone call
to your bookie.

17:16.034 --> 17:18.619
{\an1}Well, I might just have
some action for you.

17:18.704 --> 17:19.496
{\an1}If you think
you can cover it.

17:19.579 --> 17:21.165
Course I can.
I can handle anything.

17:21.248 --> 17:23.208
Who do you like?

17:23.291 --> 17:25.127
The CeltOoh.

17:25.210 --> 17:26.670
A traditionalist.

17:26.753 --> 17:27.838
Mm-hmm.

17:27.921 --> 17:30.048
No points with that.

17:30.132 --> 17:31.258
Even-steven.

17:31.341 --> 17:34.344
{\an3}How much?

17:36.263 --> 17:39.183
Either you are very confident,

17:39.266 --> 17:41.351
very rich or very stupid.

17:41.435 --> 17:43.479
{\an1}We'll find out soon
enough, won't we?

17:49.735 --> 17:52.654
{\an3}Hi, Kelly.

17:52.738 --> 17:55.741
{\an3}Sorry you had to leave
so early last night.

17:57.576 --> 18:00.496
I told you my mom
expected me home.

18:00.579 --> 18:02.623
Sorry I mentioned it.

18:02.706 --> 18:04.833
{\an6}Brenda, why don't you
just ask Dylan to
move in with you?

18:04.917 --> 18:06.335
{\an1}What is that supposed
to mean?

18:06.418 --> 18:07.669
It means you like
him coming around

18:07.753 --> 18:08.962
to cry on your shoulder.

18:09.046 --> 18:11.173
{\an1}Look, Kelly,
what is wrong with you?

18:11.256 --> 18:13.467
{\an1}Dylan and I have gone
through a lot together,

18:13.550 --> 18:14.885
{\an1}and I think,
at a time like this,

18:14.968 --> 18:16.845
{\an1}he needs as many friends
as he can get.

18:16.929 --> 18:18.180
I'm sorry.

18:18.263 --> 18:21.934
{\an3}I'm just going through
a lot right now.

18:22.017 --> 18:23.185
We all are.

18:23.268 --> 18:26.480
I know, I'm sorry.

18:26.563 --> 18:28.190
Yeah.

18:28.273 --> 18:29.858
See ya.

18:31.902 --> 18:33.904
(toilet flushing)

18:37.449 --> 18:39.159
{\an3}You heard that,
didn't you?

18:39.243 --> 18:42.579
This isn't a competition,
you know.

18:42.663 --> 18:45.874
This is Dylan's feelings
you're talking about.

18:45.958 --> 18:48.961
I know.

18:50.712 --> 18:53.799
Ever since the funeral, it's
like I can't even talk to him.

18:53.882 --> 18:55.759
Nothing I say cheers him up.

18:55.843 --> 18:57.761
Why don't you both back off
a little?

18:57.845 --> 18:59.847
You're right.

19:00.514 --> 19:03.392
Thanks.

19:15.571 --> 19:17.489
{\an3}Hey, buddy.
How you doing?

19:17.573 --> 19:20.033
I can't do it, man.

19:20.117 --> 19:22.035
{\an1}I mean, I just,
I can't be here, I...

19:22.119 --> 19:22.744
I wake up in the morning

19:22.828 --> 19:24.413
{\an1}and for the first
few seconds,

19:24.496 --> 19:25.622
before I open my eyes,

19:25.706 --> 19:27.082
{\an1}I think everything's
gonna be the same.

19:27.165 --> 19:28.584
And then it hits me.

19:28.667 --> 19:29.877
That he's gone

19:29.960 --> 19:31.086
{\an1}and it's never gonna
be the same and...

19:31.169 --> 19:33.088
{\an1}and coming to school
just seems stupid.

19:33.172 --> 19:34.089
Let's cut out of here.

19:34.173 --> 19:35.090
Go shoot some pool, huh?

19:35.173 --> 19:36.258
Nah.

19:36.341 --> 19:37.759
Glad to know your heart's
in the right place, man,

19:37.843 --> 19:39.887
I think I should hang out
by myself for awhile.

19:39.970 --> 19:40.804
See ya.

19:40.888 --> 19:43.182
ANDREA:
<i>I've been wracking my brains</i>

19:43.265 --> 19:43.724
{\an1}trying to come up
with leads,

19:43.807 --> 19:45.601
and then it hit me...

19:45.684 --> 19:46.977
there's a great story,

19:47.060 --> 19:47.436
{\an1}right there in front
of my nose.

19:47.519 --> 19:49.354
There often is.

19:49.438 --> 19:50.898
You just gotta
sniff it out.

19:50.981 --> 19:51.940
So what do you got?

19:52.024 --> 19:52.900
Well, we haven't done

19:52.983 --> 19:55.110
this month's senior
profile yet, right?

19:55.193 --> 19:56.778
{\an3}Right.

19:56.862 --> 19:59.781
I want to interview
Dylan McKay.

19:59.865 --> 20:01.617
Interesting.

20:01.700 --> 20:03.619
{\an1}I don't think
that's a good idea.

20:03.702 --> 20:05.621
What do you mean
it's not a good idea?

20:05.704 --> 20:07.122
{\an3}I mean, it's definitely
newsworthy

20:07.205 --> 20:08.624
and it could
help Dylan.

20:08.707 --> 20:09.833
How?

20:09.917 --> 20:11.752
Because talking helps,
that's how.

20:11.835 --> 20:13.921
Well, you may want to believe
that, Andrea.

20:14.004 --> 20:15.422
I mean, you might even really
believe that, but we all know

20:15.505 --> 20:17.466
what's going on here.

20:17.549 --> 20:18.800
You want a good news story,

20:18.884 --> 20:19.927
{\an1}and you're willing
to use one

20:20.010 --> 20:21.136
{\an1}of your friends
to get it.

20:21.219 --> 20:22.471
Excuse me, Brandon,

20:22.554 --> 20:23.305
it's not like I'm sneaking
around publishing

20:23.388 --> 20:25.766
{\an3}the unauthorized
biography

20:25.849 --> 20:26.683
of Dylan McKay.

20:26.767 --> 20:28.143
Look, I'm just going to ask him.

20:28.226 --> 20:29.937
If he doesn't want to do it,
he can say no.

20:30.020 --> 20:30.979
{\an3}She's right,
Brandon.

20:31.063 --> 20:31.980
She's doing her job.

20:32.064 --> 20:33.982
And in this case,
it means asking the source.

20:34.066 --> 20:35.108
Well, I guess that means

20:35.192 --> 20:36.777
you're a better journalist
than I am, Andrea,

20:36.860 --> 20:38.987
'cause there's no way in a
million years I'd ever do it.

20:39.071 --> 20:42.324
I'm going to go look for Dylan
before third period, okay?

20:42.407 --> 20:44.993
Don't botherWhy? went home.

20:45.077 --> 20:46.954
Because he can't deal
with any of this, Andrea.

20:47.037 --> 20:47.496
And the last thing he's gonna
want to deal with

20:47.579 --> 20:49.706
is a nosy reporter.

20:53.794 --> 20:55.504
(phone ringing)

20:55.587 --> 20:56.672
(on answering machine):
It's Dylan.

20:56.755 --> 20:58.090
You kno(beep) to do.

20:58.173 --> 21:00.050
Hi, Dylan, it's Andrea.

21:00.133 --> 21:02.302
Are you there?

21:05.806 --> 21:08.517
Well, I just wondered
if you felt up to some company.

21:08.600 --> 21:09.810
But I, I guess you're not there.

21:09.893 --> 21:11.144
So I'll just call you later...

21:11.228 --> 21:13.063
Andrea, wait, uh, I'm here.

21:13.146 --> 21:15.065
Hi, Dylan.

21:15.148 --> 21:17.818
Uh, Brandon told me
that you, uh, went home.

21:17.901 --> 21:21.321
Yeah, I... just had a little
trouble putting one foot

21:21.405 --> 21:21.738
in front of the other today.

21:21.822 --> 21:23.865
Well, I, um...

21:23.949 --> 21:25.117
Look, I just wanted to say

21:25.200 --> 21:27.077
if there's anything I can do
for you...

21:27.160 --> 21:28.453
You know, like,

21:28.537 --> 21:30.539
like if you want to talk
or something,

21:30.622 --> 21:31.707
I'm, I'm a great listener.

21:31.790 --> 21:33.667
Thanks. I, uh...

21:33.750 --> 21:34.876
appreciate that.

21:34.960 --> 21:37.754
Uh, maybe I could come over
or something.

21:38.797 --> 21:42.718
Yeah, uh... if you want to.

21:42.801 --> 21:43.719
Great.

21:43.802 --> 21:44.720
I'll, uh,

21:44.803 --> 21:45.721
I'll come over after school.

21:45.804 --> 21:46.763
Okay.

21:46.847 --> 21:47.556
Okay, bye.

21:47.639 --> 21:50.434
Bye.

21:51.643 --> 21:53.520
♪ You're so precious to me ♪

21:53.603 --> 21:56.857
♪ I would give the world
to you ♪

21:56.940 --> 21:59.735
♪ You're so precious to me... ♪

21:59.818 --> 22:01.403
Hold it. Hold it.

22:01.486 --> 22:05.198
David, you're hitting
the consonants too hard.

22:05.282 --> 22:06.533
{\an1}You've got
to soften them up.

22:06.616 --> 22:07.743
{\an3}(sighing):
All right.

22:07.826 --> 22:08.744
Let's do it again.

22:08.827 --> 22:09.745
From the top.

22:09.828 --> 22:13.582
(lush, synthesized
pop intro plays)

22:13.665 --> 22:16.918
♪ You're so precious to me... ♪

22:17.002 --> 22:19.129
{\an3}Hi, Donna.

22:19.212 --> 22:19.588
Steve...

22:19.671 --> 22:21.757
How's it going?

22:21.840 --> 22:23.425
Well, David's been working
on this vocal

22:23.508 --> 22:25.427
for the past couple
of days.

22:25.510 --> 22:27.137
Cut.

22:27.220 --> 22:29.139
{\an1}(over speaker):
Cut.

22:29.222 --> 22:31.391
{\an1}David, let's take it again
from the top, okay?

22:31.475 --> 22:33.435
Okay.

22:33.518 --> 22:35.562
(intro begins again)

22:35.645 --> 22:39.357
{\an1}This isn't exactly
dance music.

22:39.441 --> 22:42.319
{\an1}What happened
to hip-hop?

22:42.402 --> 22:43.945
What is this, a party

22:44.029 --> 22:44.738
{\an3}or a recording
session?

22:44.821 --> 22:45.947
{\an1}We're guests
of the artist.

22:46.031 --> 22:46.656
So keep it down, okay?

22:46.740 --> 22:50.911
♪ I will die for you... ♪

22:50.994 --> 22:51.620
"Precious?"

22:51.703 --> 22:54.122
♪ I keep telling you, baby... ♪

22:54.206 --> 22:54.581
{\an1}He put this song
in his trunk

22:54.664 --> 22:57.125
two I know.ago.

22:57.209 --> 22:58.752
Cut, cut.

22:58.835 --> 23:00.170
The levels are wrong.

23:00.253 --> 23:02.839
{\an1}Hold on, we'll go again
from the top.

23:02.923 --> 23:04.966
{\an1}Maybe we should try
a different mike.

23:05.759 --> 23:07.719
So...

23:07.803 --> 23:09.679
Davey has a lot of friends, huh?

23:09.763 --> 23:12.182
{\an1}Excuse me,
I was just wondering

23:12.265 --> 23:12.641
{\an1}why you picked
this song.

23:12.724 --> 23:14.684
I mean, it's good,

23:14.768 --> 23:16.436
{\an1}but it's certainly
not one of his best.

23:16.520 --> 23:17.979
Really?
And what makes you the expert?

23:18.063 --> 23:19.648
I'm Steven Sanders.

23:19.731 --> 23:20.899
I used to be

23:20.982 --> 23:22.150
David's manager.

23:22.234 --> 23:24.152
{\an3}"Used to be" is the
key phrase there.

23:24.236 --> 23:25.821
I'm his producer.

23:25.904 --> 23:27.489
{\an3}And I think I've been
around this block

23:27.572 --> 23:28.657
{\an3}a few more times
than you have.

23:28.740 --> 23:30.617
Yeah, maybe.

23:30.700 --> 23:31.618
But what was your last hit?
"Disco Duck"?

23:31.701 --> 23:32.577
Steve...

23:32.661 --> 23:34.496
Look...

23:34.579 --> 23:36.498
{\an3}I don't know who the hell
you think you are,

23:36.581 --> 23:40.836
{\an3}but the last thing I need
in here is negativity.

23:40.919 --> 23:42.504
{\an3}So, why don't you take your
attitude out of here

23:42.587 --> 23:44.506
{\an3}before you get the
talent nervous.

23:44.589 --> 23:48.343
Fine.

23:55.058 --> 23:57.686
Uh, where's Steve going?

23:57.769 --> 23:59.688
He had to leave.

24:02.149 --> 24:04.943
Said to tell you he loved it.

24:06.570 --> 24:08.905
{\an3}Remember... no
negativity.

24:08.989 --> 24:11.825
Or you're out
the door, too.

24:11.908 --> 24:13.243
{\an3}So Davey,

24:13.326 --> 24:14.494
{\an1}everything
sounds great.

24:14.578 --> 24:15.537
Let's take it again
from the top, okay?

24:15.620 --> 24:19.249
(intro begins again)

24:22.794 --> 24:23.670
SPORTSCASTER:
The Celtics down by 18.

24:23.753 --> 24:25.881
Parrish has fouled out
of the game

24:25.964 --> 24:27.048
at the end of the third quarter.

24:27.132 --> 24:29.759
Oh, that's it,
the fix is in.

24:29.843 --> 24:31.845
How much you got
Enough.line, pal?

24:31.928 --> 24:34.055
This is why I didn't want
to give you Duke's number

24:34.139 --> 24:34.598
in the first place.

24:34.681 --> 24:36.808
You're out of control.

24:36.892 --> 24:38.768
I know Nat, I know.

24:38.852 --> 24:39.769
But this is it--
I win this bet,

24:39.853 --> 24:41.021
I'm through; no more.

24:41.104 --> 24:42.814
{\an1}And what if you don't
win this bet?

24:42.898 --> 24:44.774
Don't even think about it.

24:44.858 --> 24:46.318
You should.

24:49.321 --> 24:51.239
DYLAN:
<i>Hey, would you like some tea?</i>

24:51.323 --> 24:51.990
ANDREA:
<i>Sure.</i>

24:52.073 --> 24:53.742
{\an1}Well, they say
it calms the nerves.

24:53.825 --> 24:56.119
{\an3}Oh, is that
what they say?

24:56.203 --> 24:58.121
Mm-hmm.

24:58.205 --> 24:59.414
{\an3}Well...

24:59.497 --> 25:00.332
(clears throat)

25:00.415 --> 25:01.791
...they say the same
thing about Scotch,

25:01.875 --> 25:04.628
{\an3}but with tea,
there's no hangover.

25:04.711 --> 25:06.254
(classical music playing)

25:06.338 --> 25:08.423
Could not...

25:08.506 --> 25:09.966
be in school today.

25:10.050 --> 25:11.593
{\an1}Well, if anybody deserves
to feel like that, it's you.

25:11.676 --> 25:13.595
{\an3}Hmm.

25:13.678 --> 25:15.263
But, you know,
this is nice.

25:15.347 --> 25:17.265
{\an3}I mean, being
here with a girl

25:17.349 --> 25:17.766
{\an3}who's not really
my girlfriend.

25:17.849 --> 25:19.935
{\an1}(laughs)

25:20.018 --> 25:22.604
That's because you don't have
to worry about impressing me.

25:22.687 --> 25:25.774
{\an3}Yeah, or hurting
your feelings or...

25:25.857 --> 25:27.776
{\an3}Well, I can
just be myself,

25:27.859 --> 25:28.610
{\an3}and there's no
strings attached.

25:28.693 --> 25:30.820
{\an3}You don't want
anything from me.

25:30.904 --> 25:34.115
{\an3}Everybody
else does.

25:34.199 --> 25:36.952
Brenda, Kel,

25:37.035 --> 25:38.995
especially my dad.

25:39.079 --> 25:41.623
Why? What did he want?

25:41.706 --> 25:45.001
{\an3}He wanted me to be
the man he never was.

25:45.085 --> 25:45.835
What's wrong with that?

25:45.919 --> 25:48.797
{\an3}It just seems a
little hypocritical.

25:48.880 --> 25:50.632
I hate a hypocrite.

25:50.715 --> 25:52.842
{\an1}Do you think your dad
was a hypocrite?

25:52.926 --> 25:55.804
I used to; I did.

25:55.887 --> 25:57.722
{\an3}I mean, but then
there toward the end,

25:57.806 --> 25:59.808
{\an3}I realized that that's
just the only way

25:59.891 --> 26:02.477
{\an3}he knew how
to live life.

26:02.560 --> 26:03.812
{\an3}So I accepted it
on his terms.

26:03.895 --> 26:05.814
Then he died.

26:05.897 --> 26:07.816
{\an1}Then why don't you continue
to accept him?

26:07.899 --> 26:10.110
{\an1}I mean, why go change
the terms now?

26:11.903 --> 26:14.322
You're pretty smart.

26:14.406 --> 26:15.657
(laughs):
Oh.

26:15.740 --> 26:16.908
{\an1}Yeah, that's what
I've been told.

26:16.992 --> 26:21.454
No, I mean, you're
smart about people.

26:21.538 --> 26:23.623
Like I said,

26:23.707 --> 26:24.708
I'm a good listener.

26:27.085 --> 26:29.296
Dylan, um, I was thinking
on my way here--

26:29.379 --> 26:31.506
and I don't want you
to take this

26:31.589 --> 26:32.799
{\an1}the wrong way--
but, uh,

26:32.882 --> 26:35.844
I was wondering

26:35.927 --> 26:38.888
if you'd be interested
in being the subject of, um,

26:38.972 --> 26:39.848
{\an1}this month's
senior profile.

26:39.931 --> 26:42.142
Ah, strings.

26:42.225 --> 26:43.977
I should have known better.

26:44.060 --> 26:45.854
No strings.
I mean, you can say no.

26:45.937 --> 26:48.648
I said no...

26:48.732 --> 26:50.775
to the <i> Times, Daily News,</i>
<i>People</i> magazine.

26:50.859 --> 26:52.694
Why should I talk to you?

26:52.777 --> 26:55.363
Because I'm your friend.

26:55.447 --> 26:58.700
Why don't we keep it that way?

27:00.285 --> 27:01.911
